Description.val:
The AIM-9X Block II/II+ Sidewinder (AIM-9X Blk II/II+) continues the evolution of the AIM-9 series of missiles. This missile program delivers a launch and leave, air combat munition that uses passive Infrared (IR) energy to acquire and track enemy air targets and complements the radar guided Advanced Medium Range Air-to-Air Missile (AMRAAM). F/A-18 first shot, first kill opportunities while conducting basic fighter maneuvering (dogfighting) Within Visual Range (WVR) are essential for aircrew survival. The AIM-9X provides these opportunities with unmatched offensive and defensive capabilities against threats WVR, even when IR countermeasures are employed. The AIM-9X also provides limited short range capability in the Beyond Visual Range (BVR) air-to-air battle. Anti-tamper features have been incorporated to protect improvements inherent in this design. 

The AIM-9X Block II missile is critical for completing fighter aircraft loadout in order to enable engagement of threats identified in the National Defense Strategy (NDS) and the Chief of Naval Operations Guidance (CNOG).

AIM-9X is a Post Milestone C, Acquisition Category IC (ACAT-IC) joint service program led by the Department of the Navy. In June 2011, the Milestone Decision Authority (MDA) established the AIM-9X Block II missile program which was approved for entry at Milestone C for Low Rate Initial Production (LRIP). The 2366 A/B certification and Acquisition Program Baseline for AIM-9X Block II was signed December 23, 2011, and the Block I program was terminated. In August 2015, the program received approval for Full Rate Production (FRP), and the Acquisition Program Baseline was re-established.

In December 2017, the program began to procure a third variant of the missile labeled the AIM-9X Block II PLUS (Block II+) to satisfy the requirements of the Joint Strike Fighter platform. This version of the missile is being produced on the same production line as the AIM-9X Block II missile. For contracting purposes, the nomenclature of the AIM-9X Block II missile is identified as AIM-9X-2 and the AIM-9X Block II+ missile is identified as AIM-9X-3.

In February 2019, the Acquisition Program Baseline for Navy and USAF was revised to increase total missile procurements from 6,000 to 11,635 missiles and to extend missile procurements through 2035.

The Navy will procure 6,615 total missiles under this Budget Line Item: 1,289 Block I missiles (885 AURs and 404 CATMs) and 5,326 Block II/II+ missiles (4,135 AURs and 1,191 CATMs). In addition, the Navy procured 63 Block I missiles in FY 2001 under the AIM-9M Modification program (48 AURs and 15 CATMs).

Justification.val:
FY 2021 provides funding to procure the seventh lot of Full Rate Production (FRP) AIM-9X Block II (Blk II) missiles, as well as the fifth lot of AIM-9X Block II Plus (Blk II+) missiles for the Navy and the Air Force. 

The program unit costs are based on all quantities procured by the US Navy, US Air Force and Foreign Military Sales customers. Total Program quantity by service includes a mix of All Up Round (AUR) missiles and Captive Air Training Missiles (CATM).

Name.@footnote: AUR Block II - This budget exhibit represents only the US Navy portion of the total program procurement.  This exhibit reflects a Navy unit cost that is congruent with the Air Force unit cost.   AUR Block II unit cost changes are heavily driven by total program quantity changes from year to year.  The majority of parts on an All Up Round (AUR) Block II are common with CATMs and Block II Plus.  As a result, the overall quantities procured (between AUR Block II, AUR Block II Plus and CATMs) to include all customers (Navy, Air Force, and Foreign Military Sales) drive the unit cost.  In addition to the Navy AUR Block II quantity decreasing from 289 in FY20 to 203 in FY21 as reflected in this exhibit, the total quantity of missile procurements (all configurations for all customers) decreases from 907 in FY20 to 705 in FY21.  In FY21, due to the reduction in overall procurement between the Navy, Air Force, and FMS customers, the unit cost has increased.  The FY20 quantity of 289 AUR's is comprised of 201 baseline and 88 OCO units.

CATMs - This budget exhibit represents only the US Navy portion of the total program procurement.  CATM unit cost changes are heavily driven by total program quantity changes from year to year.  In addition to the Navy CATM quantity decreasing from 68 in FY 2020 to 59 in FY 2021 as reflected in this exhibit, the total CATM quantity (for all customers) decreased from 88 in FY 2020 to 85 in FY 2021, resulting in a higher unit cost.
Name.val: 1.1.2) Captive Air Training Missile - Block II

Name.@footnote: AUR Block II Plus - This budget exhibit represents only the US Navy portion of the total program procurement.  Block II Plus unit cost changes are heavily driven by total program quantity changes from year to year.  Although the Navy Block II Plus procurement quantity did not change from 8 in FY20 to 8 in FY21 as reflected in this exhibit, the total procurement quantity of all tactical missiles (both Block II and Block II Plus for all customers) decreased from 822 in FY20 to 620 in FY21, resulting in a higher unit cost.
Name.val: 1.1.3) All Up Round - Block II Plus

Name.@footnote: The Engineering Change Orders line provides funding to test and qualify class 1 engineering changes proposed by the prime vendor into missile production.  The decrease in FY 2021 reflects a reduction in planned production hardware engineering changes.
DMS provides funding to design, develop, test and qualify form/fit/function replacement components to the production missile as a result of changes in sub-vendor manufacturers.

The ST/STE line provides funding for production tooling and test equipment to the AIM-9X manufacturing line to ensure missiles are produced efficiently, and within specifications.  Every 3 years the program requires production tooling to be replaced.
Name.val: 3.1.1) Special Tool & Test Equip (ST/STE) - Block II

Name.@footnote: Containers are procured to ship missiles and are procured 1 for every 4 missiles of each variant (missile variants cannot be mixed within a container).  An additional 20 containers are being procured in FY21 to increase readiness by allowing more flexibility to ship missiles with less than 4 per container.

The production tech support line includes funding to manage technical documentation, training development and delivery, production support, and management of government owned property, to support production of AIM-9X configurations.
The PSE line provides for calibration and procurement of government furnished gauges and equipment used to support missile production.
The training support line provides technical publications and training manuals to fleet maintainers.

The training equipment line includes the Telemetry (TM) Kits used to collect flight data for production qualification testing and weapons safety evaluations.  TM kits are based on missile quantities.  TM kits are manufactured by Naval Air Warfare Center, Weapons Division.
Contract support funding increases from FY20 to FY21 due to the transition from System Improvement Program III development efforts to production

The government in-house support line provides US Government Systems Engineering and Project Management support at Naval Air Warfare Centers for the production of the AIM-9X missile to ensure compliance with joint service developed cost, schedule and performance requirements.  Government support funding increases from FY20 to FY21 due to the transition from System Improvement Program III development efforts to production.
